description:
## Severity
Minor

## Dimension
Complexity / Performance / Defensive Programming

## Location
src/tools/file_index.rs:51-78 (FileIndex::walk_dir)

## Violation
```rust
fn walk_dir(&mut self, root: &Path, dir: &Path) {
    let Ok(entries) = std::fs::read_dir(dir) else { return; };
    for entry in entries.flatten() {
        ...
        if path.is_dir() {
            self.walk_dir(root, &path);   // recursive
        } else if let Ok(rel) = path.strip_prefix(root) {
            ...
        }
    }
}
```

The directory walk is recursive with no depth limit. On a symlink loop (`/a/b -> /a`) — which is not detected by the hidden/build-artifact filter — recursion is unbounded and the process stack-overflows. On a legitimately deep monorepo (>1000 nested dirs), the recursion can also exhaust the default 8MB stack. Additionally, every directory entry is read sequentially without parallelism — slow on large repos.

The walker also silently swallows `std::fs::read_dir` errors with `let Ok(entries) = ... else { return; };` — a permission-denied subdirectory truncates the index without surfacing the error. The search results then misleadingly omit files the user expects.

## Mandated refactor
1. Replace the recursive walker with the `ignore` crate (already maintained by BurntSushi for ripgrep, respects .gitignore exactly, has built-in symlink-cycle detection, parallel walking).
2. If keeping the bespoke walker: convert to iterative with an explicit VecDeque<PathBuf> work queue, track visited canonical paths in a HashSet to break symlink cycles, and log (don't swallow) read_dir errors with tracing.
3. The hidden-dir blocklist (`node_modules`, `target`, `__pycache__`, `dist`, `build`) is a partial gitignore reimplementation — strongly prefer reading `.gitignore` directly.

